#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "error_explanation"
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "error_suggestion"
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"You get this error when the name between the [code]for[/code] and [code]in[/code] is not a valid variable name, or you are missing the [code]in[/code] keyword.\n"
"\n"
"In a [code]for[/code] loop, the [code]in[/code] keyword only accepts a valid temporary variable name to assign values in each loop iteration. The loop creates a new variable with the desired name and assigns each element of the array to it."
msgstr "In einer [code]for[/code]-Schleife akzeptiert das [code]in[/code]-Schlüsselwort nur einen gültigen temporären Variablennamen, um Werte in jeder Schleifeniteration zuzuweisen. Die Schleife erstellt eine neue Variable mit dem gewünschten Namen und weist ihr jedes Element des Arrays zu."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"To fix this error, you need to ensure that the name between the [code]for[/code] and [code]in[/code] keywords is a valid variable name with no punctuation or spaces.\n"
"\n"
"For example, this code is invalid: [code]for cell_position.x in cell_positions_array:[/code] because [code]cell_position.x[/code] isn't a valid variable name.\n"
"\n"
"To access the [code]x[/code] sub-component of the variable, you need to do that inside of the loop's body:\n"
"\n"
"[code]for cell_position in cell_positions_array:\n"
"    cell_position.x += 1.0[/code]"
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"You get this error when you try to assign a value to something that is not a variable.\n"
"\n"
"You can only assign values to variables. You cannot assign values to function calls or calculations.\n"
"\n"
"For example, you cannot write [code]randi() = 5[/code] because [code]randi()[/code] is a function call, not a variable."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"Check what you wrote on the left side of the equal sign (=). Make sure it is a variable name.\n"
"\n"
"If you see parentheses () on the left side, you might be trying to assign to a function call. Remove the parentheses and the function call.\n"
"\n"
"If you are trying to check if two values are equal in a condition, use two equal signs (==) instead of one (=)."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"You get this error when you try to change the value of a constant.\n"
"\n"
"A constant is a name that holds a value that cannot change. It's like a variable, but once you set its value, you cannot replace it.\n"
"\n"
"For example, if you write [code]const MAX_SPEED = 100[/code], you cannot later write [code]MAX_SPEED = 200[/code] or [code]MAX_SPEED += 50[/code].\n"
"\n"
"Many constants are built into Godot and GDScript, and you cannot change them either. For instance, you cannot write [code]Vector2 = 5[/code] or [code]PI = 3[/code]. Constant names usually use capital letters."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"Look at what you are trying to change. If it is a constant (defined with the [code]const[/code] keyword or built into Godot), you have two options:\n"
"\n"
"1. If the value should never change, or it comes from Godot, remove the line that tries to change it.\n"
"2. If the value needs to change, use [code]var[/code] instead of [code]const[/code] when you first create it."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"You get this error when you mix spaces and tabs in your indentation. This happens when you have a space before a tab, or a tab before a space at the start of a line.\n"
"\n"
"In GDScript, you must use only tabs (not spaces) to indent your code. When you press the Tab key on your keyboard, it creates a tab character.\n"
"\n"
"If you accidentally type a space before a tab, or a tab before a space, the computer gets confused about your code's indentation."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"To fix this error, go to the line mentioned in the error message. Delete any space characters at the very beginning of the line, and remove any spaces that appear after your tab characters.\n"
"\n"
"Tab characters look like an arrow pointing at a vertical line in your code: ⇥. Spaces look like centered dots: ·. Look closely to spot the difference.\n"
"\n"
"Then, make sure the line starts with only tab characters for indentation, with no spaces mixed in."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"A cyclic reference is when a class references itself, directly or indirectly.\n"
"\n"
"It has two possible causes:\n"
"\n"
"1. You used the class name in the class itself.\n"
"2. Your code refers to another class that refers to this class, causing an endless reference cycle.\n"
"\n"
"Either way, due to how GDScript works in Godot 3, unfortunately,you cannot do this. Godot 4 should solve this problem, but you need to work around it in the meantime."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"Erase the type hint in the error line, and the problem should disappear.\n"
"\n"
"At GDQuest, when we face this error, we remove the type hints on lines causing cyclic references. It solves the problem in the vast majority of cases."
msgstr "Wenn wir bei GDQuest mit diesem Fehler konfrontiert sind, entfernen wir die Typhinweise in Zeilen, die zyklische Verweise verursachen. Es löst das Problem in den allermeisten Fällen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"The indentation of your code (the number of tab characters at the start of the line) is incorrect.\n"
"\n"
"You are missing one or more tabs, or you inserted too many.\n"
"\n"
"The computer uses those leading tab characters on code lines to know which lines of code are part of a code block, like a function."
msgstr "Der Computer verwendet diese führenden Tabulatorzeichen in Codezeilen, um zu wissen, welche Codezeilen Teil eines Codeblocks sind, wie eine Funktion."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"If the line of code with the error is right after a line ending with a colon, like a function definition, you need one extra indent level compared to the previous line.\n"
"\n"
"In other words, your line should have one more leading tab character than the function definition."
msgstr "Wenn sich die Codezeile mit dem Fehler direkt nach einer Zeile befindet, die mit einem Doppelpunkt endet, wie bei einer Funktionsdefinition, benötigst Du im Vergleich zur vorherigen Zeile eine zusätzliche Einzugsebene."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"You get this error when you wrote something that is syntactically invalid, or you are missing something to complete this line or previous lines of code.\n"
"\n"
"You need to be extremely precise when you write code for the computer. This kind of error is easy to get as all it takes is one wrong character.\n"
"\n"
"Note that this error can appear [b]after[/b] the line causing it due to how the computer reads and analyzes your code."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"The way to solve this kind of error is highly contextual. The error message should tell you which character or element it's missing.\n"
"\n"
"If the error says \"expected,\" then you're likely missing something in one of the [b]previous[/b] code lines. It could be a punctuation mark, a parenthesis, or something else.\n"
"\n"
"If it says \"unterminated,\" you are missing some character at the end of an expression, like a closing bracket. In this case, it most likely comes from the line with the error."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"You get this error when you use a special character that GDScript doesn't recognize.\n"
"\n"
"This includes accented letters (like é, à, ñ), special symbols, or characters from non-Latin alphabets in your code instructions (not in strings).\n"
"\n"
"[b]Note:[/b] Godot 4 supports special and non-Latin characters in code (Unicode characters), but this app is built with Godot 3, which does not."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"To fix this error, remove any accented letters or special characters from your variable names, function names, and other code elements.\n"
"\n"
"You can use accented characters inside text strings (between quotes), but not in the code itself.\n"
"\n"
"You can replace accented letters with their non-accented equivalents. For example, change [code]café[/code] to [code]cafe[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"This error tells you that you are missing a parenthesis (or sometimes a comma or a path).\n"
"\n"
"Three keywords in GDScript work like function calls and require parentheses: [code]yield()[/code], [code]preload()[/code], and [code]assert()[/code]."
msgstr "Drei Schlüsselwörter in GDScript funktionieren wie Funktionsaufrufe und erfordern Klammern: [code]yield()[/code], [code]preload()[/code] und [code]assert()[/code]."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "To address the error, you want to add the missing opening parenthesis, the closing parenthesis, or the comma."
msgstr "Um den Fehler zu beheben, musst Du die fehlende öffnende Klammer, die schließende Klammer oder das Komma hinzufügen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"This error happens in several cases:\n"
"\n"
"1. You wrote an identifier (variable or function name) in the wrong place.\n"
"2. You wrote a keyword like [code]var[/code], [code]func[/code], [code]for[/code], or [code]signal[/code], and you did not follow it by a name.\n"
"3. You wrote a function definition but forgot the parentheses before the colon."
msgstr ""
"1. Du hast einen Bezeichner (Variablen- oder Funktionsname) an der falschen Stelle geschrieben.\n"
"2. Du hast ein Schlüsselwort wie [code]var[/code], [code]func[/code], [code]for[/code] oder [code]signal[/code] geschrieben und keinen Namen gegeben.\n"
"3. Du hast eine Funktionsdefinition geschrieben, aber die Klammern vor dem Doppelpunkt vergessen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"If the error tells you it expected something, you likely forgot to write a name after a keyword like [code]var[/code], [code]func[/code], [code]for[/code], or [code]signal[/code], making your code invalid. Or you forgot parentheses in a function definition. You can address the error by adding the missing name or parentheses.\n"
"\n"
"If the error says you have something unexpected, you are likely missing a keyword like [code]var[/code], [code]func[/code], [code]for[/code], etc.\n"
"\n"
"Another possibility is that you need to write a colon at the end of a function definition, [code]for[/code] loop, or a line starting with [code]if[/code], [code]elif[/code], or [code]else[/code]."
msgstr "Wenn der Fehler Dir sagt, dass er etwas erwartet hat, hast Du wahrscheinlich vergessen, einen Namen nach einem Schlüsselwort wie [code]var[/code], [code]func[/code], [code]for[/code] oder [code]signal[/code] zu schreiben, wodurch Dein Code ungültig wird. Oder Du hast Klammern in einer Funktionsdefinition vergessen. Du kannst den Fehler beheben, indem Du den fehlenden Namen oder die fehlenden Klammern hinzufügst."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"This error tells you that you are missing a type somewhere. A type can be [code]int[/code], [code]float[/code], [code]String[/code], [code]Array[/code], [code]Vector2[/code], and many identifiers representing a data structure.\n"
"\n"
"Most of the time, this error occurs when you wrote a colon after a variable name but did not follow it with a type name.\n"
"\n"
"It also occurs when you write an arrow ([code]->[/code]) after the parentheses of a function definition but do not follow it with a type name."
msgstr "Dieser Fehler besagt, dass Du irgendwo einen Typ vergessen hast. Ein Typ kann [code]int[/code], [code]float[/code], [code]String[/code], [code]Array[/code], [code]Vector2[/code] und viele andere Bezeichner sein, die eine Datenstruktur darstellen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "To solve this, you need to write the name of the type after the colon, arrow (in the case of function return types), inside parentheses (for export types), or after the [code]as[/code] keyword."
msgstr "Um dieses Problem zu lösen, muss man den Namen des Typs nach dem Doppelpunkt, dem Pfeil (im Falle von Funktionsrückgabetypen), in Klammern (für Exporttypen) oder nach dem Schlüsselwort [code]as[/code] schreiben."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"The variable, function name, or class name you are trying to use does not exist.\n"
"\n"
"You most often get this error when you make typos. Maybe you swapped two letters, forgot a letter... sometimes, it's hard to spot.\n"
"\n"
"The other cause for this error is that you didn't define the variable, function, or class you're trying to access."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"To solve this error, triple-check that there is no typo in the line.\n"
"\n"
"If you can, try to go to the variable or function definition, double-click the name, copy it, and paste it where you see the error.\n"
"\n"
"If you don't see any typo, then you need to ensure that you defined the variable, function, or class you are referring to."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"You can only use keywords like [code]break[/code] or [code]continue[/code] in a loop. Outside a loop, they are invalid.\n"
"\n"
"The [code]continue[/code] keyword means \"jump to the next iteration of the loop.\" And the [code]break[/code] keyword means \"end the loop right now and jump to the first line of code after the loop block."
msgstr "Das Schlüsselwort [code]continue[/code] bedeutet \"Zur nächsten Iteration der Schleife springen\". Und das Schlüsselwort [code]break[/code] bedeutet \"beende die Schleife jetzt und springen zur ersten Codezeile nach dem Schleifenblock."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"If you wrote one of these keywords outside a loop, you need to remove it.\n"
"\n"
"If you are trying to use it inside a loop, your indentation is most likely at fault. You may need to insert one or more leading tab characters to the keyword."
msgstr "Wenn Du versuchst, es innerhalb einer Schleife zu verwenden, ist Dein Einzug höchstwahrscheinlich schuld. Möglicherweise musst Du ein oder mehrere führende Tabulatorzeichen in das Schlüsselwort einfügen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"When the computer talks about a constant expression, it expects a fixed value, a fixed calculation, or the name of an existing constant.\n"
"\n"
"In other words, it wants something that can never change. This is why the computer will reject function calls and variables where it needs a constant expression."
msgstr "Mit anderen Worten, es will etwas, das sich niemals ändern kann. Aus diesem Grund lehnt der Computer Funktionsaufrufe und Variablen ab, wenn er einen konstanten Ausdruck benötigt."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"You need to replace function calls or variables with a constant value like a whole number, decimal number, string, vector, a predefined array, etc.\n"
"\n"
"You can also use arithmetic operators like multiplications (*), additions (+), and so on."
msgstr "Funktionsaufrufe oder Variablen durch einen konstanten Wert wie eine ganze Zahl, eine Dezimalzahl, eine Zeichenfolge, einen Vektor, ein vordefiniertes Array usw. ersetzt werden."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"When defining a new class, you need to follow a specific pattern. You must write the name in plain text, starting with a letter.\n"
"\n"
"We typically write class names in PascalCase: with a capital letter at the start of every word that composes the class name."
msgstr "Beim Definieren einer neuen Klasse musst Du einem bestimmten Muster folgen. Du musst den Namen im Klartext schreiben, beginnend mit einem Buchstaben."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"To fix this error, replace whatever you put after the 'extends' or 'class_name' keyword by a name without spaces and starting with a capital letter.\n"
"\n"
"You can optionally use numbers in the name, but not in the first position."
msgstr "Um diesen Fehler zu beheben, ersetze alles, was Du nach dem Schlüsselwort \"extends\" oder \"class_name\" eingeben hast, durch einen Namen ohne Leerzeichen und beginnend mit einem Großbuchstaben."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"You are trying to define a function or variable that already exists; You can't do that.\n"
"\n"
"Perhaps the function or variable already exists in the current code file, but it may also be in a parent class that this GDScript code extends."
msgstr "Möglicherweise ist die Funktion oder Variable bereits in der aktuellen Codedatei vorhanden, aber es kann sich auch in einer übergeordneten Klasse befinden, die dieser GDScript-Code erweitert."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"In the app, your code extends some built-in Godot code that's not visible to you.\n"
"\n"
"When that happens, you need to either rename your function or variable to one that will not collide with an existing one or remove this line of code."
msgstr "Wenn das passiert, musst Du entweder deine Funktion oder Variable in eines umbenennen, das nicht mit einem vorhandenen kollidiert, oder diese Codezeile entfernen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"You are trying to define a signal that already exists; You can't do that.\n"
"\n"
"Perhaps the signal already exists in the current code file, but it may also be in a parent class that this GDScript code extends."
msgstr "Möglicherweise ist das Signal bereits in der aktuellen Codedatei vorhanden, aber es kann sich auch in einer übergeordneten Klasse befinden, die dieser GDScript-Code erweitert."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"In the app, your code extends some built-in Godot code that's not visible to you.\n"
"\n"
"When that happens, you need to either rename your signal to one that will not collide with an existing one or remove this line of code."
msgstr "Wenn das passiert, musst Du entweder dein Signal in eines umbenennen, das nicht mit einem vorhandenen kollidiert, oder diese Codezeile entfernen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"The function you're trying to define exists in a parent class, so your definition overrides the parent class's function.\n"
"\n"
"When you override a parent class's function, the new function must match the parent. The new function should have the same number and type of parameters as the parent class.\n"
"\n"
"For example, if the parent has two arguments, you need your new function also to have two arguments. If you use type hints in your function definitions, the argument types must match the parent class."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "You need to check the parent class's function and its definition in the code reference. Then, you need to edit your function definition to have the same number and type of parameters as the parent class."
msgstr "Du musst die Funktion der übergeordneten Klasse und ihre Definition in der Codereferenz überprüfen. Anschließend musst Du ihre Funktionsdefinition bearbeiten, um die gleiche Anzahl und den gleichen Typ von Parametern wie die übergeordnete Klasse zu haben."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "This whole class of errors has to do with calling functions with either the wrong number of arguments or the wrong kind of argument. You will need to use the error message to see what is going wrong."
msgstr "Diese ganze Klasse von Fehlern hat mit dem Aufrufen von Funktionen zu tun, die entweder die falsche Anzahl von Parametern oder die falsche Art von Parametern haben. Du musst die Fehlermeldung lesen, um zu sehen, was schiefläuft."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "You need to either remove, add, or change the values you're trying to pass to the function to solve this issue. To know exactly how many arguments you need, you need to check the code reference. It will show you the function definition and the mandatory arguments."
msgstr "Du musst die Werte, die Du an die Funktion übergeben möchtest, entweder entfernen, hinzufügen oder ändern, um dieses Problem zu beheben. Um genau zu wissen, wie viele Parameter benötigt werden, musst Du die Codereferenz überprüfen. Es zeigt die Funktionsdefinition und die nötigen Parameter."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"All the values in your code have a specific type. That type can be a whole number (int), a decimal number (float), text (String), and so on. There are tons of possible types, and you can even define your own!\n"
"\n"
"When you make any operation, the computer compares the types you are using.\n"
"\n"
"Some types are compatible, and some are not. For example, you cannot directly add a whole number to a text string. You first need to convert the number into text.\n"
"\n"
"You'll need to read the error message to see what is not matching because there are many possible cases."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"If the error mentions the assigned value type not matching the variable, the problem is on the right side of the equal sign (=).\n"
"\n"
"If the error talks about the return type not matching the function, then it is the value after the return keyword that is problematic.\n"
"\n"
"If the computer talks about an invalid operand, then the issue is that the operation does not exist for the type you're trying to use. For example, while you can add two 2D vectors, you can't add a whole number or text to a 2D vector."
msgstr "Wenn der Computer über einen ungültigen Operanden spricht, besteht das Problem darin, dass der Vorgang für den Typ, den Du verwenden möchtest, nicht vorhanden ist. Während Du beispielsweise zwei 2D-Vektoren hinzufügen kannst, kannst Du einem 2D-Vektor keine ganze Zahl oder Text hinzufügen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"GDScript supports type inference. The computer will automatically recognize the type of value you are working with. In some cases, though, it can't figure it out.\n"
"\n"
"When that happens, you need to specify the type yourself or remove type inference altogether for this variable."
msgstr "GDScript unterstützt type inference (Typrückschluss). Der Computer erkennt automatisch den Typ des Wertes, mit dem Du arbeitest In einigen Fällen kann jedoch nicht vom Wert auf den Typ geschlossen werden."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"The simplest way to solve this error is to remove types for this variable or this function's arguments. Otherwise, you can manually specify the value type after the colon.\n"
"\n"
"We recommend specifying the type whenever possible to reap the typing system's benefits."
msgstr "Die einfachste Möglichkeit, diesen Fehler zu beheben, besteht darin, Typen für diese Variable oder die Parameter dieser Funktion zu entfernen. Andernfalls kannst Du den Typ der Variable nach dem Doppelpunkt manuell angeben."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"There is an issue with the return value of your function. There are two main cases here:\n"
"\n"
"1. Your function is a void function, thus it should not return a value. This includes functions with the '-> void' syntax and class constructors ('_init()').\n"
"2. You specified a return type for your function, but you are not returning a value in all possible branches (if, elif, and else blocks) or at the end."
msgstr ""
"1. Ihre Funktion ist eine void-Funktion, daher sollte sie keinen Wert zurückgeben. Dazu gehören Funktionen mit der Syntax '-> void' und Klassenkonstruktoren ('_init()').\n"
"2. Du hast einen Rückgabetyp für deine Funktion angegeben, aber Du gibst keinen Wert in allen möglichen Verzweigungen (if, elif und else-Blöcke) oder am Ende zurück."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"When your function is 'void', you should never return a value. You can use the 'return' keyword to end the function early, but you should never write anything after that.\n"
"\n"
"When you use a return type, you must always return something at the end of the function or in every branch (if, elif, and else block) of the function."
msgstr "Wenn Deine Funktion \"void\" ist, solltest Du niemals einen Wert zurückgeben. Du das Schlüsselwort 'return' verwenden, um die Funktion vorzeitig zu beenden, aber Du solltest danach nie etwas schreiben."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "Godot was unable to load your script, yet the language checker found nothing wrong."
msgstr "Godot konnte dein Skript nicht laden, trotzdem hat der Sprachprüfungsserver keinen Fehler erkannt."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "Please click on the \"report\" button at the top and please let us know."
msgstr "Bitte klicke oben auf den Button \"Melden\" und lasse es uns wissen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "You called a function inside itself. This will loop forever."
msgstr "Du hast eine Funktion in sich selbst aufgerufen. Dies wird sich für immer wiederholen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "There are valid reasons for using recursive functions, but none of them are part of this course, so this cannot be a valid solution."
msgstr "Es gibt gute Gründe für die Verwendung rekursiver Funktionen, aber keiner von ihnen ist Teil dieses Kurses, so dass dies keine gültige Lösung sein kann."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "You wrote a while loop with a condition that is always true (like [code]while true:[/code] or [code]while(true):[/code]) without a [code]break[/code] statement inside it. This creates an infinite loop that will freeze your game."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "To fix this, you need to either add a [code]break[/code] statement inside the loop so it can exit when a certain condition is met, or change the while loop condition to something that will become false. For example: [code]while position.x < 100: position.x -= 10[/code]."
msgstr ""

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid ""
"The computer reached the end of the line of code, but the line had a syntax error.\n"
"The most common case is when you forget to close a string: you have opening quotes, but you forget to add a matching closing quote."
msgstr ""
"Der Computer hat das Ende der Codezeile erreicht, aber die Zeile hatte einen Syntaxfehler.\n"
"Der häufigste Fall ist, dass du vergessen hast, eine Zeichenfolge zu schließen: Du hast öffnende Anführungszeichen, aber vergessen, ein passendes schließendes Anführungszeichen hinzuzufügen."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "Double-check that you are not missing a quote character or that the quote character you used to start the string is the same as the one you used to close the string."
msgstr "Vergewissere dich, dass kein Anführungszeichen fehlt oder dass das Anführungszeichen, mit dem du die Zeichenfolge begonnen hast, mit dem übereinstimmt, das du zum Schließen der Zeichenfolge verwendet hast."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
msgid "The sub-variable you are trying to access does not exist."
msgstr "Die Untervariable, auf die du zuzugreifen versuchst, existiert nicht."

#: script_checking/error_database.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"You probably have a typo in the name of the sub-variable that you are trying to access.\n"
"\n"
"Ensure that you don't have a capital letter where you should have a lowercase letter and vice versa."
msgstr "Vergewissere dich, dass du keinen Großbuchstaben anstelle eines Kleinbuchstabens verwendest und andersherum."

#: course/glossary.csv course/documentation.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid "explanation"
msgstr "Wiederholung (Iteration)"

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"Member functions are functions attached to a specific value type, like arrays, strings, or dictionaries. We also call them methods.\n"
"\n"
"For example, arrays have member functions like [code]array.append()[/code].\n"
"\n"
"You can only call the function on an array, using the access operator ([code].[/code]) to access it, as shown above."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"Member variables are variables attached to a specific value type, like a vector's [code]x[/code] and [code]y[/code] sub-variables. We also call them [i]properties[/i] or [i]fields[/i] of the vector.\n"
"\n"
"To access a member variable, you must first write the value's name followed by the access operator ([code].[/code]). For example, [code]position.x[/code]."
msgstr "Membervariablen sind Variablen, die Teil eines bestimmten Werttyps sind, z. B. die Untervariablen [code]x[/code] und [code]y[/code] eines Vektors. Wir nennen sie auch [i]Properties[/i] oder [i]Felder[/i] des Vektors."

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"A parameter is a variable you create as part of a function definition.\n"
"\n"
"It allows you to reuse the function more by having values that vary in the function's body."
msgstr "Parameter ermöglichen es dir, Funktionen zu erstellen, die an mehreren Stellen in deinem Code verwendet werden können, indem du der Funktion bei Aufrufen andere Werte als Parameter mitgibst."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"A radian is a unit of measurement of angles based on the circle's circumference.\n"
"\n"
"We tend to use degrees more in our daily lives, but in computer programming, and especially in games, radians are common.\n"
"\n"
"An angle of [code]2 * PI[/code] radians corresponds to 360 degrees. And an angle of [code]PI[/code] radians corresponds to 180 degrees."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"In computer programming, a type is the class of a value. For example, whole numbers like [code]3[/code], [code]11[/code], and [code]255462[/code] are all of type [code]int[/code] (short for integer).\n"
"\n"
"The computer uses types to determine which operations are valid between two values and when they're undefined."
msgstr "In der Computerprogrammierung ist ein Typ die Klasse eines Werts. Beispielsweise sind ganze Zahlen wie [code]3[/code], [code]11[/code] und [code]255462[/code] alle vom Typ [code]int[/code] (kurz für integer)."

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"In computer code, an iteration is one repetition of some process or code. We typically use the term with loops, where one iteration is one run of the loop's code.\n"
"\n"
"When talking of algorithms, an iteration can mean a full pass of the algorithm on a data set."
msgstr "Im Computercode ist eine Iteration eine Wiederholung eines Prozesses oder Codes. Wir verwenden den Begriff normalerweise mit Schleifen, wobei eine Iteration ein Durchlauf des Codes der Schleife ist."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"In math, a vector is a list of numbers. In games, we often use 2D and 3D vectors: respectively, lists of two and three numbers.\n"
"\n"
"We use that to represent a direction and magnitude or intensity in space. For example, you can use a vector to represent the direction and speed at which a character or a vehicle moves.\n"
"\n"
"Vectors can seem daunting at first because they are pretty abstract, but as you will see, they'll simplify code tremendously."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"An argument is a value you pass to a function when you call it. For example, in the function call [code]rotate(0.5)[/code], the value [code]0.5[/code] inside the parentheses is an argument.\n"
"\n"
"A function can take no arguments, one argument, or multiple arguments. Arguments can be required or optional.\n"
"\n"
"When a function requires multiple arguments, you separate them with commas. Here's an example: [code]jump(50, 100)[/code]\n"
"\n"
"When you [i]call[/i] a function, we call the values in parentheses [i]arguments[/i].\n"
"\n"
"But when you [i]write[/i] a function definition, we call them [i]parameters[/i] instead. Here's an example:\n"
"\n"
"[code]func move_to_position(x, y):[/code]\n"
"\n"
"In this function definition, [code]x[/code] and [code]y[/code] are [i]parameters[/i]."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"An array is a list of values. In GDScript, arrays can contain [i]any[/i] types of value.\n"
"\n"
"To create an array, you write comma-separated values in square brackets: [code]var three_numbers = [1, 2, 3][/code]\n"
"\n"
"In games, we use arrays all the time to store lists of characters in a party, lists of items in inventory, lists of spells the player unlocked, and so on. They're everywhere.\n"
"\n"
"Arrays are a fundamental value type in computer programming. You'll find arrays in pretty much any programming language."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid "Assigning a value to a variable means that you store a value inside the variable. You do this with the equal sign ([code]=[/code])."
msgstr "Das Zuweisen eines Werts zu einer Variablen bedeutet, dass Du einen Wert in der Variablen speicherst. Das geschieht mit dem Gleichheitszeichen ([code]=[/code])."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"A dictionary is a data structure that maps values with key-value pairs. When you give the dictionary a key, it finds and gives you back the corresponding value.\n"
"\n"
"In GDScript, keys can be many things. We often use text strings or numbers, but you're not limited to that. A [code]Vector2[/code] can also be a valid key, which is handy to map a grid cell to a unit or an item in a grid-based game.\n"
"\n"
"You will often use dictionaries to associate bits of data in your games. For example, we could use them to associate an equipment's name with its weapon stats in a database.\n"
"\n"
"Like arrays, they are a fundamental data type that you will see in many programming languages and use a lot."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"A for loop instructs the computer to repeat a set of instructions once for each value in an array.\n"
"\n"
"In each loop iteration, the compiler extracts one value from the array and gives you access to it in the loop's body.\n"
"\n"
"For loops run code a limited amount of times: one per value in the array. It is different from while loops that keep repeating code until a condition is met.\n"
"\n"
"We recommend favoring for loops when you can. They're safer and easier to use than while loops."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"A function is a group of code instructions you give a name. When you define a function, you can call it any time to run all the instructions it contains.\n"
"\n"
"You can modify a function's behavior with parameters. Parameters are variable names that you write in the function definition. You can then use them in the function's body to make your code adapt to different cases.\n"
"\n"
"Also, functions can optionally return a value to the code calling it."
msgstr "Du kannst das Verhalten einer Funktion mit Parametern ändern. Parameter sind Variablennamen, die Du in die Funktionsdefinition schreibst. Du kannst sie dann im Hauptteil der Funktion verwenden, um Deinem Code an verschiedene Fälle anzupassen."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid "An increment is the amount by which a value changes in your code."
msgstr "Ein Inkrement ist der Betrag, um den sich ein Wert im Code ändert."

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"In computer programming, instructions are a single operation the computer recognizes and can execute.\n"
"\n"
"For example, a function call, an addition, or assigning a value to a variable."
msgstr "In der Computerprogrammierung sind Anweisungen eine einzelne Operation, die der Computer erkennt und ausführen kann."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"Variables are a tool to give a name to values you want to store in your code and change over time.\n"
"\n"
"For example, a character's health: when the character takes a hit, you want it to go down. When healing, you want the health to go back up.\n"
"\n"
"You can create a variable named [code]health[/code] to represent the health.\n"
"\n"
"Then, every time you write the keyword [code]health[/code] in your code, the computer will fetch the corresponding value in its memory for you.\n"
"\n"
"Variables work a bit like product labels in a supermarket. They are names that you attach to some value. Any time, you can take the label and stick it onto a new product or, in that case, a new value."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid ""
"A while loop instructs the computer to keep running code based on a condition. While the condition is true, the loop keeps running.\n"
"\n"
"When coding while loops, you must be careful: they will keep running infinitely and freeze your game if you get the condition wrong.\n"
"\n"
"That's why we recommend using the safer for loop whenever you can.\n"
"\n"
"However, there are still essential cases in which we use while loops, like processing files, processing computer code, or for powerful algorithms."
msgstr ""

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid "We talk about a loop or a function's body to refer to the lines of code that are part of the loop or function."
msgstr "Wir sprechen über eine Schleife oder den Körper einer Funktion, um auf die Codezeilen zu verweisen, die Teil der Schleife oder Funktion sind."

#: course/glossary.csv
#, fuzzy
msgid ""
"Returning a value is the process of sending a value to the place where you call a function.\n"
"\n"
"It happens when a function uses the [code]return[/code] keyword followed by a value, for example: [code]return -1[/code]."
msgstr "Dies geschieht, wenn eine Funktion das Schlüsselwort [code]return[/code] gefolgt von einem Wert verwendet, z. B.: [code]return -1[/code]."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid "A collection of valuable and reusable code bundled together by other programmers to save you time. All programmers use code libraries."
msgstr "Eine Sammlung an nützlichen und wiederverwendbaren Code der von anderen Programmierern zusammengefasst wurde um Zeit zusparen nennt man Bibliothek oder Library. Jeder nutzt sie."

#: course/glossary.csv
msgid "In computer graphics, a sprite is an image you display on the screen. We generally use this word to talk about moving images, like a character, a monster, or an item falling on the ground."
msgstr "In Computer Grafiken nennt man Bilder die auf dem Bildschirm angezeigt werden können \"Sprites\". Wir nutzen dieses Wort typischerweise um über sich bewegende Bilder, wie zum Beispiel Charaktere, Monser oder Gegenstände zu reden."

